<font color="#FF0000">WE CONFUSED SANITY WITHREALITY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 19 15:41:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gary, <br><br>
I know what you mean and what you felt.<br><br>
Often I felt they dropped them in too close and at other times felt they weren't close enougth. <br><br>
Heck, we figured that if we couldn't read the return address on the ordinance being dropped, the gooks were too far away to bother to shoot at. Sometimes we just confused sanity with reality, common sense and fiction, sometime it was all the same.<br><br>
The Corpsmen during operation Foster, Doc Mc, worked hard on saving a couple of Marines near me who had sucking chest wounds, remember scrambling around trying to locate aluminum foil from gum wrappers to plug up the hole.<br><br>
I wish I could find him. Where do Vietnam era corpsmen, go after the war? Is there a list somewhere where you can call for information, If I had his real name I might be able to find him. <br><br>
He wanted me placed on the next chopper out during that op,  the concussion from a chicon grenade, had thrown me backwards, and paralyzed my legs so that all I could do was crawl around. Great guy, saved a lot of Marines lives, during that operation. I never went, until the end of the operation when I could no longer walk because of the jungle rot. Doc remained with us through December of 1967. Then he was gone, never learned his real name. <br>

